Java.template: $package   import plm.universe.turtles.Turtle;  public class HexaKoch extends Turtle { $body  	public void run() { 		drawCurve((Integer)getParam(0),(Double)getParam(1)); 	} }

Scala.name: HexaKoch

Python.name: HexaKoch
Python.correction:
# BEGIN TEMPLATE 

def hexaKoch(levels, length):
		# BEGIN SOLUTION 
		if levels == 0:
			forward(length)
		else:
			hexaKoch(levels-1, length*.14)
			left(120)
			for i in range(5):
				hexaKoch(levels-1, length*.14)
				right(60)
			left(180)
			hexaKoch(levels-1, length*.14)
		# END SOLUTION	

def drawCurve(levels, length):
	hexaKoch(levels, length)

# END TEMPLATE

drawCurve(getParam(0), getParam(1))

initialWorlds.name: hexaKoch(0,200)
initialWorlds.about:
The universe of turtles

This is an adaptation of LOGO for the Programmer's Learning Machine.

It is directly inspired from the work of the mathematician Seymour Papert in the 60's. Inspired from the swiss psycholog Jean Piaget, he came up with a learning method called LOGO to teach programming to young childs. The world is full of turtles which leave a painting where they go and which respond to simple orders.

Functions to move the turtle

void forward(double steps)
void backward(double steps)
Moves forward or backward of the requested amount of steps. 
void right(double angle)
void left(double angle)
Turns left or right of the given angle (in degrees). 
double getX()
double getY()
Returns the current position of the turtle. Note that the point (0,0) is on the top left corner, as it is often the case in Computer Science. 
void setX(double x)
void setY(double y)
void setPos(double x, double y)
Teleports the turtle to a new position (without leaving any trace). 
void moveTo(double x, double y)
Moves the turtle to a new position. 
void circle(double radius)
Draw a circle of the specified radius centered on the turtle. 
void hide()
Hides the turtle. 
void show()
Shows the turtle back. 
boolean isVisible()
Returns whether the turtle is currently visible. 
void clear()
Removes any trail on the sheet. 
double getHeading()
Returns the current heading of the turtle (in degrees). 
void setHeading(double angle)
Sets a new heading to the turtle (in degrees).

Functions about the pen

void penUp()
Moves the pen up (turtles have pens, not brushes as buggles). The turtle will not leave any trace during its subsequent moves. 
void penDown()
Moves the pen down. The turtle will leave a trace during its subsequent moves. 
boolean isPenDown()
Returns the current pen position as a boolean. 
Color getColor()
Returns the current pen color. 
void setColor(Color color)
Changes the pen color.

Other functions

boolean isSelected()
Returns whether the current turtle is selected in the graphical interface.

instructions.en:
Snow hexagon

This time, we will draw the curve that is known as the (6, 0.14)-Koch curve. This means that you have to grow 6-sided polygons on the segments, and that the length should be multiplied by 0.14 at each recursion level.

For the record, the original Koch curve is the (3, 1/3)-Koch curve, the Snow square would be (4,1/3)-Koch curve while the Snow pentagon is also called the (5, 0.4)-Koch curve. If you want, you can switch to the creative mode in the menu and explore freely other Koch curves. Just change the initial call to hexaKoch to what you want.

For further reference, please see http://ecademy.agnesscott.edu/~lriddle/ifs/kcurve/kcurve.htm.
instructions.fr:
Hexagone de neige

Cette fois, nous allons dessiner une courbe surnomme la courbe de Koch-(6; 0,14). Cela signifie que nous allons faire pousser des hexagones (des polygones 6 faces) sur les segments, et que les longueurs doivent tre multiplies par 0,14 chaque tage de la rcursion.

Pour info, la courbe de Koch originale est la (3; 1/3). Le carr de neige est la courbe (4; 1/3). Le pentagone de neige est la courbe (5; 0,4). Si vous le souhaitez, vous pouvez passer en mode cratif pour explorer d'autres courbes de Koch. Remplacez simplement l'appel hexaKoch par ce que vous voulez.

Pour plus d'informations, rfrez vous http://ecademy.agnesscott.edu/~lriddle/ifs/kcurve/kcurve.htm.
